<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   House President Opposes Turkey at Council of Europe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC3101215994 Nicosia CYPRUS NEWS AGENCY in English 1745 GMT 
31 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC3101215994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia CYPRUS NEWS AGENCY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nicosia, Jan 31 (CNA)--The president of the House of 
Representatives Alexis Galanos disputed Turkey's credentials at 
the Council of Europe because of its illegal occupation of 
Cyprus' northern part and its attitude towards Turkey's own 
people. 
  Speaking before the plenary session of the parliamentary 
assembly of the Council of Europe in Strasbourg, Galanos argued 
that Turkey did not comply with the Council's principles, nor 
did it respect democratic processes, human rights or 
international law and order. 
  In an interview with the Cyprus radio, the House president 
warned that this time he did not intend to put Turkey's 
membership of the Council to the vote and asked that double 
standards policies for existing members and new members be 
abolished. 
  He believed it was high time this matter was dealt with 
directly to avert the possibility of allowing the Turkish 
Cypriots to upgrade their representation to the Council and 
consequently pave the way for recognition of their illegal 
administration in Cyprus' Turkish-occupied areas. 
  Turkish troops invaded and occupied 37 per cent of the 
republic's territory. Turkey has refused to comply with U.N. 
resolutions calling for the immediate withdrawal of its troops 
from the island. 
  "We are fighting a big battle in the Council of Europe," 
Galanos said and advocated an enlarged Cypriot representation to 
carry on the battle for Cyprus. 
  Meanwhile, the island is playing host to Lord Finsberg, 
rapporteur for the Cyprus problem at the Political Committee of 
the Council of Europe. 
  Lord Finsberg, here for contacts to prepare a report on 
Cyprus, met Monday [31 January] with President Glavkos 
Kliridhis. Later in the day, he had a meeting with U.N. 
secretary-general's resident representative to Cyprus Gustave 
Feissel. 
  He told Cyprus radio after the meeting that judging from 
what 
he had heard at his meetings here, he believed talks on the 
Cyprus issue would yield good results. 

</TEXT>

