<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Head Resigns Following Devaluation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA3101170194 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1550 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA3101170194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Jan 31 (A.A) -- Central Bank Director 
General Bulent Gultekin announced his resignation on Monday [31 
January], five days after an 13.6 percent devaluation of the 
Turkish lira. 
  Gultekin, at his post since August 26, said the atmosphere 
of 
confidence was fading and there was a need for a medium-term 
economic programme. 
  Bankers had been calling for the governor to resign after 
what they said was monetary mismanagement which led to the 
devaluation last Wednesday night. 
  Gultekin was quoted as saying the Central Bank had used all 
the necessary tools to soothe the markets, thrown into disarray 
by currency chaos. 
  He said the bank `was left unaided' since two international 
credit agencies cut Turkey's rating on January 14. 
  `My resignation will not lead to a new crisis,' Gultekin 
told 
reporters at a news conference. 
  `I hope my resignation will bring the seriousness of 
economic 
problems onto the agenda', he said. 

</TEXT>

