<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciampi: Government To Step Down After Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU3101154594 Paris AFP in English 1530 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU3101154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, Jan 31 (AFP) -- Italian Prime Minister Carlo 
Azeglio Ciampi said here Monday [31 January] that he does not 
plan to run in the upcoming general elections in Italy and that 
his government would step down after the vote. 
  "My government was created last May to deal with a difficult 
phase of transition," Ciampi said during a press conference held 
after a meeting with Austrian Chancelor Franz Vranitzky. "The 
decision to hold new elections (27-28 March) puts an end to this 
transitional period and I have no intention of being a candidate 
during the elections." 
  Ciampi has been running a caretaker government since the 
dissolution of parliament earlier this month. 
  His decision not to run in the elections comes as Italy's 
political parties are trying to forge alliances ahead of the 
elections. Left-wing parties had been looking to Ciampi as 
their possible candidate for the post of prime minister. 

</TEXT>

