<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bulgarian Leader Meets International Counterparts in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets Demirel, Others </H4>
<F P=102> AU3001192094 Sofia BTA in English 1838 GMT 30 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3001192094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Davos, January 30 (BTA) -- The meetings of 
Bulgarian Prime Minister Lyuben Berov continued here today. 
  He had talks with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel. The 
two agreed that the relations between the two countries are 
dynamic and that the cooperation in trade, investments and the 
Black Sea Economic Cooperation should be further promoted. They 
also discussed the situation in the former Yugoslavia and the 
Balkans in general. This spring the Bulgarian foreign minister 
is expected to visit Turkey and Turkish Prime Minister Tansu 
Ciller, Bulgaria. President Demirel denied reports in the 
Turkish press alleging that Kurdish terrorist organizations were 
transferring their bases from Germany to Bulgaria. 
  Prof. Berov's meeting with Kazakhstan's President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev expressed a mutual desire for promotion of the 
bilateral contacts. The two arranged a visit of a group of 
Bulgarian businessmen to Kazakhstan. Mr. Nazarbayev proposed 
that a joint bank be set up to facilitate the settlements 
between the two countries. 
  Prime Minister Berov met with Greek First Deputy Minister of 
Economy Y. Papantoniou [name as received] to consider measures 
for upgrading the road and railway links between the two 
countries. They also discussed the Bulgarian transport 
minister's forthcoming visit to Greece. 
  Mr. Jacques de Larosiere, president of the European Bank for 
Reconstruction and Development, handed Prof. Berov a list of the 
Bulgarian projects approved by the bank for financing. Mr. 
Larosiere briefed the Bulgarian prime minister on the bank's new 
short-term loan policy. 
  The Bulgarian prime minister also met with Jean-Claude Paye, 
secretary-general of the Organization for Economic Cooperation 
and Development. The two discussed the priorities in the 
development of the Bulgarian-G-24 ralations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38341 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu022__a94008" </HT>


