<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   European Union Considers GATT Negotiations Closed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0102152194 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1654 GMT 31 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0102152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed mf, rp: "GATT: Meeting Among Group of Four </F>
Powers. Last Attempt To Improve Offers Before Marrakesh"; as 
released by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Geneva, 31 January (ATS) -- The world commercial 
powers of the Group of Four (United States, European Union, 
Canada, and Japan) held a meeting in Geneva on Monday [31 
January] in order to prepare for the signing of the Uruguay 
Round trade agreements in Marrakesh (Morocco) in April. These 
agreements were concluded among 117 states in Geneva last 
December. The Americans still hope to persuade Japan to improve 
its offer of market access. 
  The United States thinks that the negotiations with Japan on 
market access are not over. The Japanese, on the other hand, 
retort that the discussions on this subject are closed. 
Washington expects from Tokyo a larger reduction in customs 
duties on certain products (timber, copper, and alcohol), 
according to a diplomatic source. 
<H5>  "Balanced Context" </H5>
  "If we can improve market access with Japan, we will do so, 
but this must be done in a balanced context," Hugo Paemen, 
European Union deputy director general of foreign economic 
relations, said. 
  "An improvement is still possible," Mr. Paemen said. 
However, the issues so far discussed are essentially marginal. 
"We will not reopen the negotiations," the European official 
stressed, adding that it was impossible to go back on what had 
been achieved. The Europeans think they have completed their 
negotiations with everybody. 
  A meeting of experts from the four commercial powers will be 
held on Tuesday with the aim of putting clearly down on paper 
the lists of tariff offers. The Group of Four is due to meet in 
around 10 days for a final verification of the offers. This 
meeting will take place shortly before 15 February, the deadline 
set by the GATT secretariat for the submission of the final 
lists. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

