<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   IG Metall Reports `Over 107,000' Metal Workers on Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102164194 Hamburg DPA in German 1434 GMT 1 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0102164194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt/Main (DPA) -- According to IG Metall 
[metal workers' trade union], more than 107,000 employees in 482 
companies had participated in the warning strikes in the west 
German metal industry by midday Tuesday [1 February]. According 
to the Frankfurt headquarters of the trade union, more metal 
workers have been called upon to participate in rallies in the 
afternoon, for instance in the Hesse towns of Giessen and 
Kassel, as well as in Kempten in Bavaria. 
  The focus of the activities was North Rhine-Westphalia, 
where, according to IG Metall, about 57,000 workers from 351 
companies went on strike for one to three hours. At a total of 
eight rallies --- in Dueren, Hattingen, Siegburg, and 
Luedenscheid, among other places -- the metal workers protested 
the employers' wage policy. 
  The trade union counted about 20,000 participants in various 
protest rallies in Lower Saxony. In Bavaria, which was the 
focus of the protests yesterday, more than 13,000 metal workers 
participated in warning strikes. In Baden-Wuerttemberg 9,000 
employees from 14 companies went on strike for up to four hours. 
Further protest actions took place in Hesse, 
Rhineland-Palatinate, Saarland, and Berlin. 

</TEXT>

