<F P=100> BENELUX </F>
<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister: Air Attacks on Bosnia Conditional </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0102144794 Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT in Dutch 1 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BR0102144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Wio Joustra: "Netherlands Troops Receive Ground </F>
Support"] 
  [Excerpts] The Hague -- The Netherlands troops opposing the 
warring factions in eastern Bosnia do not have to rely solely on 
limited air support, but can also rely on the support of ground 
troops from other countries such as the United Kingdom and 
France. According to UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali, the 
international community must show that it is serious about 
Bosnia. [passage omitted] 
  This afternoon in the Lower House, Defense Minister Ter Beek 
will argue on the basis of Butrus-Ghali's letter that the launch 
of air strikes to neutralize Serbian artillery positions around 
Srebenica and Zepa is not on the agenda. 
  Asked for his reaction to the letter, Ter Beek said through 
a 
spokesman on Monday [31 January] that attacking Serbian 
positions would be too great a risk for UNPROFOR [UN Protection 
Force] units already present in Bosnia. Various groups have 
argued this point in previous debates. Limited air support will 
only be used when resistance is such that the battalion's 
ability to carry out its mission is jeopardized or if it needs 
to defend itself. 

</TEXT>

