<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: Liberals Fall, Center Democrats Rise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0102163094 Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 30 Jan 
94 p 9 </F>

<F P=103> PM0102163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Erik Bjorn Moller: "Liberals Losing Ground"] </F>
  [Text] If it were not for the fact that Gallup's latest 
opinion poll took place before departing Research Minister Svend 
Bergstein (Center Democrat) raised his voice and drew attention 
to the Center Democrats and his ministry, a few people might 
have been tempted to believe that the Center Democrats' latest 
rise had to do with the fired minister's final broadside. 
  This is not the case. Nevertheless, in today's Gallup 
opinion poll it is a fact that once again the Center Democrats 
-- as they did in November -- are succeeding in keeping their 
nose above the threshold for representation in the Folketing -- 
this time with five deputies to boot. 
  On the other hand the Liberal Party has fallen from 30.5 
percent in December to 27.5 percent this month. If there were a 
Folketing election tomorrow, the Liberal Party would have 49 
seats -- as against 57 in December. 
  Nevertheless, Liberal Party taxation spokesman Peter 
Brixtofte has faith in a landslide when the election comes. 
"Our standing is high regardless. It is still double what it 
has been in the past. The other things are temporary 
fluctuations. Things go up and down. But with these figures I 
would like to urge the Center Democrats to return to the fold 
where they belong," Brixtofte said. 
  Neither a Liberal Party-Conservative People's Party-Progress 
Party bloc nor the present government would have an absolute 
majority. The Unity List would again enter the Folketing. 


Political Index 1994 

