<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Latest Poll Shows Rehn's Lead Shrinking </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0102132094 Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 30 Jan 94 
p 7 </F>

<F P=103> PM0102132094 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Bjarne Nitovuori: "New Poll: Rehn's Lead </F>
Shrinking"] 
  [Excerpt] The latest opinion poll, published yesterday in 
HELSINGIN SANOMAT, shows that Elisabeth Rehn's (Swedish People's 
Party) lead over her rival in the final round of the 
presidential election, Martti Ahtisaari (Social Democratic 
Party), is now very narrow. 
  Of those interviewed who were willing to state their 
preference, 53 percent promised to vote for Rehn and 47 percent 
for Ahtisaari. This difference falls within the margin of error 
of 3 percent in either direction. In theory it is possible 
therefore that the state of public opinion is level at 50-50. 
  The poll was carried out by Finska Gallup on 26 and 27 
January. In a similar poll carried out the day after the first 
round of the election, Rehn led by 56 percent to 44 percent. 
  Both polls interviewed around 1,000 people, 24 percent of 
whom were unwilling to state their preference or announced that 
they did not intend to vote. 
  Of those interviewed last week, 11 percent had already 
voted. 
The Rehn-Ahtisaari balance among them was even. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

