<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundeswehr To Participate in UN Mission in Georgia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202154394 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1435 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- Germany is to send four members of 
the Bundeswehr to Georgia as part of the UN observer mission 
(UNOMIG). Government Spokesman Dieter Vogel added in Bonn today 
that the observer group is to provide support in the creation of 
a permanent peace in Georgia. The deployment of the German 
soldiers is limited to six months. Vogel said it is the first 
UN deployment of this nature on the territory of the former 
Soviet Union and the first involvement of German soldiers in 
such a mission. 
  Federal Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel stressed that 
"preventive diplomacy" is becoming an increasingly important 
element in peacekeeping as the main aim of the United Nations. 
The mission in Georgia serves that purpose. As the first UN 
deployment on the territory of the former Soviet Union, it aims 
to back the efforts of the conflicting parties for a 
comprehensive political solution in Georgia. The conflicting 
parties have approved German participation in UNOMIG, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

