<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Court Acquits 3 of Exporting Poison Gas Plant to Iraq </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102144894 Berlin DIE WELT in German 1 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0102144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [DPA report: "Acquittals in Darmstadt Poison Gas Lawsuit"] </F>
  [Text] Darmstadt -- Yesterday the Darmstadt Land Court 
acquitted the managing director and two employees of the former 
Karl Kolb group (Dreiech) of the charge that they had delivered 
poison gas plants to Iraq in the eighties. The multipurpose 
plants they exported were not especially constructed for the 
production of chemical weapons, it was stated. In its opinion, 
the court referred to unfit penal provisions. The proceedings 
led to the "bitter finding" that the FRG had made the export of 
weapons-grade chemical plants possible for 30 years. Four other 
employees of the firm will be sentenced today. With three 
managers of the former firm WET in Hamburg, one of the acquitted 
persons still has to answer for the export of an alleged bomb 
production line. 

</TEXT>

