<H3> <TI>   Metalworkers Union Calls `Token Strikes' 1 Feb </TI></H3>
<H4>   17,000 Strike in North Rhine-Westphalia </H4>
<F P=102> LD0102124794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1207 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0102124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wuppertal (DDP/ADN) -- By noon today, about 17,000 
workers in the metalworking and electrical engineering industry 
in North Rhine-Westphalia had joined token strikes. The 
regional executive of the Wuppertal branch of IG Metall 
(Engineering and Metalworkers' Union) said the strikes are 
focused on the towns of Aachen, Gevelsberg, Gummersbach, 
Hattingen, Leverkusen, Luedenscheid, Olpe, Remscheid, and 
Wuppertal. 
  The largest rally was in Wuppertal, where 6,400 engineering 
workers marched through the streets to protest employers' 
demands for a workers' pay cut. The fourth round of 
negotiations ended last week without agreement on a date for 
their resumption. 

</TEXT>

