<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pakistan's Bhutto Briefs Press Following UNCHR Address </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0202040794 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network in Urdu 0200 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0202040794 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Urdu </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto has urged the 
international community to force India to end its atrocities in 
occupied Kashmir before a meaningful dialogue is held between 
Pakistan and India. She was speaking to a news conference held 
after she addressed the United Nations Commission on Human 
Rights in Geneva. Benazir Bhutto said she addressed the 
Commission in order to mobilize international public opinion and 
force India to take solid steps to allow human rights 
organizations into occupied Kashmir, release detained Kashmiri 
leaders, permit television crews and journalists to visit 
Kashmir, and reduce the number of troops there. She said the 
world should not ignore human rights violations in occupied 
Kashmir. Keeping this in view, it is imperative to implement 
the UN resolutions. This problem is pertinent not only for 
today, but also for the future. 
  When the prime minister was asked whether Pakistan will 
consider demands for a sovereign Kashmir, she said that no such 
demand has yet been made. This so-called demand will resurrect 
the entire issue of the 1947 partition of the subcontinent into 
an independent Pakistan and India. She said that while 
reviewing this demand, the demands for freedom by Sikhs, Tamils, 
and other groups in India should also be kept in mind. 
  The prime minister said that Pakistan has presented 
proposals 
to India at the international level time and again on the issue 
of nuclear nonproliferation, but India has rejected all of them. 
  Regarding her visit to Bosnia today, Benazir Bhutto said she 
and her Turkish counterpart Tansu Ciller are visiting Bosnia to 
express their solidarity with Bosnian Muslims. She said their 
efforts are intended to ensure the implementation of the London 
Accord on Bosnia. She said that decisions to lift the arms 
embargo and implement a cease-fire should be made within the 
purview of the London Accord. 
  Earlier, addressing the Human Rights Commission in Geneva, 
Benazir Bhutto urged the international community to take steps 
to stop the carnage in occupied Kashmir and exert pressure on 
India to withdraw its troops from the occupied valley. She 
said: It is time for the international community to force India 
to release the Kashmiri leaders; lift all of its draconian 
emergency laws; stop its Army from committing atrocities in 
Kashmir; and allow international human rights organizations and 
representatives of humanitarian institutions and the mass media 
to visit occupied Kashmir, ascertain the facts, and provide help 
to the suffering Kashmiris. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

