<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciller Departs on Humanitarian Visit to Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0202111494 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 0800 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0202111494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has stated that Turkey 
would like the guns in Bosnia-Herzegovina to be silenced as soon 
as possible, adding that Turkey will continue to contribute in 
every way to achieve this end. Ciller further stressed the need 
to continue with the uninterrupted transport of humanitarian aid 
to the Bosnians. Ciller departed for Bosnia on a humanitarian 
visit this morning. 
  In a statement prior to her departure at Ankara's Esenboga 
Airport, Ciller stated that she will first visit Zagreb where 
she will meet with Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto. 
Ciller explained that they will depart for Sarajevo after being 
briefed by UN military officials. Indicating that their visit 
is solely for humanitarian purposes, Ciller said: A community 
in the midst of Europe has been waging a war of survival for the 
last two years, enduring great sufferings to protect their 
existence. Unfortunately, the world has been a silent spectator 
to this tragedy. The aim of this visit is to show the Bosnians 
once more that we have not forgotten them and to call on 
international public opinion to be more sensitive to this issue, 
our visit being another proof of our determination. 
  Recalling that the United Nations is constantly trying to 
extend humanitarian aid to Bosnia-Herzegovina, Ciller stressed 
the need for the uninterrupted continuation of this aid. 
  Later, Religious Affairs Director Mehmet Nuri Yilmaz 
presented Ciller with 30,000 German marks and 250 copies of the 
Koran. 
  Ciller is accompanied by Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin on 
her 
visit to Bosnia. Necmettin Cevheri, state minister and acting 
prime minister, several ministers, and other officials saw 
Ciller off at the airport. 

</TEXT>

