<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pangalos on Chances of Bosnian Crisis Spreading South </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0102171994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1600 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0102171994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Members of the Chamber of Deputies' Foreign 
Relations Committee have expressed their concern that the war in 
the former Yugoslavia could spread south. The deputies 
participated in a briefing on the agenda of the Greek presidency 
of the European Union. Alternate Foreign Minister Theodhoros 
Pangalos, who briefed the members of the Foreign Relations 
Committee, expressed the view that the possible spread of the 
war to the south will depend on the stance of the Kosovar 
Albanians. 
  [Begin Pangalos recording] We have every reason to believe, 
and we hope for it and try to use our influence toward it, that 
the Albanian side will show moderation. It is not logical to 
assume that the Serbs would open a new front at a time when they 
are engaged in other disputes, such as with Croatia, which is 
not an active dispute right now, and Bosnia, where they are 
forced to take the steps that [words indistinct]. Let us hope 
that the Albanians, who have legitimate demands for autonomy and 
education, will not raise the issue of independence, something 
that will create a conflict with consequences that can not be 
estimated. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

