<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alphandery Sees `Gradual Improvement' in Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0102202894 Paris AFP in English 1745 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0102202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Feb 1 (AFP) -- Recent data gathered by the 
INSEE Institute show "gradual improvement" in the French 
economy, Economics Minister Edmond Alphandery said on Tuesday [1 
February]. 
  He told correspondents that the reports by the National 
Statistics and Economic Studies Institute "confirm the 
government's scenario of a gradual improvement of economic 
activity in France. Hence it would be inappropriate to change 
course." 
  But he added that "There is still one worrisome point: the 
irregular trends in consumption." He said that household 
consumption of manufactured products would have been up in 
December, except that the problems of the auto sector pulled the 
increase down to zero. 
  "The rebound continued in January, and the partial 
indicators 
are rather promising," he said. 
  As to French unemployment, now at 12 percent and expected to 
rise further, the minister said that "The uptrend has not been 
halted, but things on the job front are gradually coming to look 
less dark." 
  Turning to interest rates, Alphandery said he would be 
"greatly surprised if we do not observe, in Europe and in 
France, a gradual return to the normal yield curve" (long-term 
rates higher than short-term rates). 
  As to possible recapitalization of major bank Credit 
Lyonnais, he said he was waiting for release of 1993 financial 
reports before making a decision. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

