<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciampi Says Interest Rates To Fall in 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0102132794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1901 GMT 31 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0102132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ciampi on Interest Rates, Austerity </F>
Measures"] 
  [Text] Rome, 31 Jan (ANSA) -- Interest rates will continue 
to fall in 1994, according to Prime Minister Carlo Azeglio 
Ciampi, who on Monday [31 January] said the government does not 
have enough information at this time to evaluate the need for 
further austerity measures. 
  Speaking to reporters on his flight back to Rome from 
Vienna, 
Ciampi said that it was "very easy to predict" that interest 
rates will continue to fall this year, although not as much as 
they did in the last three quarters of 1993. 
  "Between April and December of 1993," Ciampi said, "interest 
rates fell between four and five points. Today they are at 7 to 
7.5 percent. At this rate, they should drop to below 3 percent 
this year but I fear that will be difficult." 
  How interest rates go will depend on what happens in Italy 
and abroad, he added. "I think that none of us in April thought 
it would have been possible to cut interest rates in just eight 
months to today's levels." 
  Asked whether his government planned additional austerity 
measures to reduce the deficit in the near future, Ciampi 
replied that the first public finance report will be available 
in March. "At that time we will see what changes need to be 
made.... At this time I have no indications because it is not 
easy to have any after the first month of the year." 
  Continuing recession in Europe however will certainly have 
negative effects on Italy's primary surplus, Ciampi said. Lower 
interest rates can reduce the burden of debt servicing but in 
March, "and only in March," Ciampi stressed, will it be possible 
to compare forecasts to reality. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

