<F P=101> Switzerland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stich Meets With Uzbek President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2801161194 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1943 GMT 28 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2801161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed mf: "Meeting Between Otto Stich and Uzbek </F>
President. The Talks Related Primarily to Economic Questions"; 
as released by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Bern, 27 Jan (ATSA) -- Uzbek President Islam Karimov 
had a 45-minute meeting on Thursday evening [27 January] in Bern 
with Confederation President Otto Stich. The two presidents 
essentially discussed economic problems, according to Mario 
Carrera, spokesman for the Federal Department of Finance (DFF). 
  Bern and Tashkent said they wanted to strengthen their 
relations, the DFF spokesman added. Switzerland and Uzbekistan 
signed two agreements last year, one relating to economic 
cooperation and the other to investment protection. The Uzbek 
president expressed the wish that cooperation between the two 
countries should not stop there. 
  Mr. Karimov, who reminded Mr. Stich of his country's major 
economic potential, stressed the positive role played by the big 
Swiss banks in Uzbekistan, Mr. Carrera added. The two 
presidents deemed it necessary to continue the economic reforms 
in the framework set out by the IMF. Uzbekistan is a member of 
the voting group headed by Switzerland within the Bretton Woods 
institutions. 
  Mr. Stich and Mr. Karimov also discussed the general 
political situation in Central Asia, particularly the case of 
Tajikistan. Following this short meeting with the president of 
the Confederation, the Uzbek president is due to go to Davos to 
participate in the economic forum. 

</TEXT>

