<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   France Presses for Immediate Opening of Tuzla Airport </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202133894 Paris AFP in English 1327 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0202133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Feb 2 (AFP) -- The French Foreign Ministry 
insisted Wednesday [2 February] that the airport in the northern 
Bosnian town of Tuzla be reopened immediately to relief flights 
and condemned the shelling of the airport by Serb troops. 
  Foreign Ministry spokesman Richard Duque warned that 
Tuesday's shelling of the airport was a direct affront to the 
international community and recalled the recent decision by the 
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) to consider air 
strikes to ensure the reopening of the airport. 
  The airport has been shut down since May 1992. 
  Meanwhile, Spanish Foreign Minister Javier Solana stopped 
briefly in Split Wednesday on his way to the southern Bosnian 
town of Medjugorje where he is to meet with the Spanish UN 
battalion based there. 
  Solana said prior to his departure from Madrid that the 
Spanish troops would have to be redeployed to new positions in 
case of NATO air strikes. 
  He added that although the Spanish troops would remain in 
the 
former Yugoslavia throughout the winter months, the Spanish 
Government may reconsider the situation if a peaceful solution 
to the conflict appears unlikely. 
  "Perhaps after winter we should make an in-depth analysis of 
the situation with other countries involved and make a decision 
if a peaceful solution to the conflict has not been reached by 
then," he said. 
  On Tuesday, the commander of Spanish troops in Bosnia, 
Colonel Luis Carvajal, said UN peacekeepers would be in danger 
in case of NATO air strikes as they are ill prepared to respond 
to any retaliatory attacks and Serb reaction to the strikes 
would be "unpredictable." 
  Earlier this month, the opposition Popular Party in Spain 
also demanded the withdrawal of the Spanish troops from Bosnia 
since it said the situation on the ground there was becoming 
increasingly dangerous. 
  Spain has 1,180 UN peacekeeping troops deployed in the 
former 
Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

