<F P=100> ITALY &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Catania Elections Yield Surprise Results </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0202141494 Milan IL GIORNALE in Italian 1 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BR0202141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Milan IL GIORNALE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Elections at Catania, Good-Bye to </F>
the Left"] 
  [Text] In the elections for the renewal of the Provincial 
Council, the "progressive" representative takes third place 
only. The contenders in the final ballot are the candidate from 
the right (with 32.8 percent of the votes) and the candidate 
from the center (26.3 percent). 
  These are surprise results in the provincial elections in 
Catania. Little more than six months after the choice of Enzo 
Bianco as "progressive" mayor of Palermo, the city has suddenly 
turned its back against the left, placing on the final ballot 
the National Alliance candidate Nello Musumeci and the Pact for 
Italy politician Stello Maugiameli. Rejected with no chance of 
appeal are Andrea Scudieri (PDS [Democratic Party of the Left], 
Communist Renewal, AD [Democratic Alliance], Rete, and the 
Greens) and Maurizio Pellegrino (socialist and PDS circles plus 
League). 
  National Alliance leader Gianfranco Fino is exultant: "This 
is the proof that we are not destined to fall into the hands of 
the left." Satisfied too are [Pact for Italy leader] Mario 
Segni, [Italian Republican Party Secretary] Giorgio La Malfa, 
and the CCD [Democratic Christian Center] neocentrists. Tolling 
the death knell, for the left, [PDS Secretary] Achille Occhetto 
recited a late "mea culpa." "We should not be disheartened, but 
work hard, because the battle will be a hard one." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38465 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu023_j_94006" </HT>


