<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe Outlines Defense Budget, Cuts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0202180894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1614 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0202180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- Defense Minister Volker Ruehe 
intends to implement the 1.25 billion [German] mark [DM] budget 
cuts adopted by the Cabinet chiefly in the areas of equipment, 
personnel, and international missions undertaken by the 
Bundeswehr. He announced the details in Bonn today before the 
Bundestag Defense Committee. 
  He said that just under DM600 million of the cuts will be 
achieved by means of immediate measures. Individual measures to 
account for the remaining sum of around DM650 million will be 
decided during the year, Ruehe said. The list of immediate 
measures comprises a total of six items. It provides, among 
other things, for a reduction in Bundeswehr strength to 345,000 
soldiers by yearend. 
  The budget allocation for international missions is to be 
cut 
by DM100 million. If the Bundeswehr is needed further in this 
area in 1994, additional funding is to be provided. Funds for 
military procurements are to be cut by DM220 million. Some 
DM165 million less are to be spent on civilian and military 
personnel. The suspension of all military exercises in the 
second half of 1994 is intended to achieve savings of a further 
DM45 million. 
  Some DM60 million are to be spent on rebuilding the 
infrastructure in the new [eastern] states. Savings of around 
DM10 million altogether are also to be made in the navy and air 
force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

