<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Allows Mixed Oxide Fuel Elements for Reactor </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302101094 Berlin DIE TAGESZEITUNG in German 2 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE TAGESZEITUNG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Klaus Wittmann report: "Plutonium Fuel Rods"] </F>
  [Text] Gundremmingen -- For the first time worldwide, 
mixed oxide (MOX) fuel elements are permitted for use in a 
boiling water reactor. After a year-long controversy over the 
authorization, this was decided by the Bavarian Health Ministry 
yesterday. In first statements, the Bavarian Greens and the 
"Alliance for Protection From MOX" talked of a "disastrous false 
decision." 
  It is an alarming world premiere and completely 
incomprehensible that Germany is the trailblazer with this 
nonsense, Deputy Raimund Kamm from the Greens said. In the 
course of the authorization proceedings, even the International 
Atomic Energy Agency in Vienna objected to the use of MOX fuel 
elements in boiling water reactors. Such reactors only have one 
cooling cycle. 
  However, Bavarian Environment Minister Peter Gauweiler 
thinks 
that the objections are unfounded. An international safety 
analysis has shown that it can be safely used, he said. More 
than 40,000 people had objected to the use of MOX and there had 
been fierce controversies in the hearing in February 1993. The 
people who made objections complained about the vexatious 
transaction of the proceedings. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

