<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Rehn on Welfare State, EU, Russia, Presidency </TI></H3>
<H4>   * Max Jakobson Assesses Rehn </H4>
<F P=102> 94P20325B Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT in Finnish 27 Jan 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20325B </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Unto Hamalainen: "Unabashed Candidate of the </F>
West"] 
  [Text] "The uppermost impression from the interview with 
Elisabeth Rehn is that she is the first Finnish presidential 
candidate who unabashedly manifests a Western orientation. There 
is nothing strange in itself regarding this. Finland has indeed 
always been a Western country, but we have been influenced by 
our legacy from the Cold War. We have been constrained by this," 
explained [former Foreign Minister] Max Jacobson. 
  In his view, Rehn is right in her understanding of the 
provisions in the Paris Peace Treaty in that more than just its 
military aspect has become obsolete: Finland from the very 
beginning never accepted limitations contained in the treaty. 
They do not conform to conditions of a democratic country. 
  In foreign policy, Rehn tightly follows the official line. 
She has been a supporter of the European Union, and according to 
Jakobson, it is natural for Rehn to say that she will be able to 
influence [the conditions] of membership also before the 
referendum. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

