<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bomb Explodes at Goethe Institute; ELA Implicated </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0302065294 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 0500 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0302065294 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A bomb exploded at 0138 today at the German Goethe 
Institute on 14 Omiros Street in Athens. Approximately one half 
hour earlier an unidentified person who said he represented ELA 
[Revolutionary People's Struggle] telephoned ELEVTHEROTIPIA 
newspaper and warned about the explosion. The police cordoned 
off the area to prevent casualties. However, the men of the 
antiterrorism squad did not manage to enter the building before 
0420 today because there was nobody in charge to open it. The 
bomb was planted in the ladies room on the first basement level 
where it caused considerable material damage. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38491 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu023_p_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-023 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Papoulias Returns From U.S. Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0202220494 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0202220494 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Alkis Malidhis] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias described his 
talks with high-ranking U.S. officials in the framework of the 
dialogue between the European Union [EU] and United States as 
positive. Papoulias returned today to Athens and detailed the 
U.S. Government's position regarding the Skopje issue. 
  [Begin Papoulias recording] The United States is more 
interested in the normalization of relations between Greece and 
Skopje than in upgrading diplomatic relations between itself and 
Skopje. I think that we should move in this direction. 
Therefore, the normalization of Greek-Skopjean relations will 
depend on the acceptance of the conditions we set by [Macedonian 
President] Kiro Gligorov so that we can proceed with a dialogue 
on the name issue. The Greek position on the issue is known. In 
the meantime, we should try to create a better climate in the 
relations between the two countries. [end recording] 
  Papoulias also referred to yesterday's statement by UN 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali in New York that the UN 
hopes for a meeting between Greek and Skopjean experts. 
  [Begin Papoulias recording] I have no information on what 
Butrus-Ghali said. [end recording] 
  Regarding his meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher, the Greek foreign minister also said that the U.S. 
Government holds positions on the crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
that will be developed in the coming weeks. He added that both 
the EU and the United States insist on the promotion of a peace 
plan and reject military interventions. 
  [In the same newscast, Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio 
Network carries the following dispatch by correspondent Nikolaos 
Meletis on Foreign Minister Papoulias' remarks before his 
departure from Washington: "During a friendly talk with Greek 
correspondents, Foreign Minister Papoulias also said that 
Gligorov appears tough, encouraged by diplomatic recognitions, 
and seeks to gain something more. Papoulias said that Gligorov 
does not realize that the most important thing is to establish 
good relations with Greece, which is the only regional country 
that guarantees the borders and future of his country." 
  [In a recorded statement Papoulias commented "I do not 
understand why he does not proceed with something which, as they 
say, he had agreed to during talks with Former Greek Prime 
Minister Konstandinos Mitsotakis. 
  ["The foreign minister stressed that negotiations on the 
name 
will be difficult, as our country insists on the historically 
justified position not to accept a name that contains the term 
Macedonia or its derivatives. 
  ["Referring to the Cyprus issue, Foreign Minister Papoulias 
stressed that the confidence-building measures do not touch the 
substance of the issue. He also expressed his concern over the 
possibility that Turkish Cypriot Leader Rauf Denktas will use 
the confidence-building measures to prolong a fruitless dialogue. 
  ["Commenting on the U.S. State Department's human rights 
report, the foreign minister stressed that this report does not 
have anything to add or take away and that it is repetition. 
The report contains information that the Americans have, and 
one can agree or disagree with them, the minister said. 
Papoulias concluded by expressing concern about the credibility 
of the sources used to formulate the report."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

