<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundesbank Announces 8-Percent Growth in Money Supply </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302105794 Hamburg DPA in German 0939 GMT 3 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0302105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt/Main (DPA) -- In 1993 the M3 money supply 
evidently did not keep to the target. On Thursday [3 February] 
the Bundesbank announced that the annual money supply growth 
rate was 8.1 percent (preliminary value) in December. In 
November the M3 money supply (cash in circulation, sight 
deposits, time deposits with maturities of less than four years, 
and savings deposits) had grown with an annual rate of 7.2 
percent. The Bundesbank had set the target zone for 1993 at 4.5 
to 6.5 percent. This year the guardians of the currency are 
aiming at monetary growth between 4 and 6 percent. 

</TEXT>

