<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Decrease in Asylum Applications Continues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202120094 Hamburg DPA in German 1130 GMT 2 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0202120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- The number of people applying for asylum in 
Germany continues to decrease. In January, the authorities 
registered 13,154 applicants, which is 879 fewer than last 
December, Erwin Marschewski, domestic-policy spokesman for the 
Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union [CDU/CSU] 
Bundestag group, told DPA on Wednesday [2 February]. Even the 
December number of 14,033 registered asylum-applicants had been 
described by the Federal Interior Ministry as being the lowest 
figure since March 1991. 
  Marschewski pointed out than in January 1993 as many as 
36,279 persons applied for asylum. The decrease in the number 
of applicants by more than half, which was initiated last July 
when the new asylum law came into force, is "most encouraging," 
Marschewski said. 

</TEXT>

