<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unions: Eastern Unemployment Higher Than Acknowledged </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202105694 Hamburg DPA in German 1006 GMT 2 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0202105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin -- According to the Federation of German 
Trade Unions [DGB], the job deficit in the new laender amounted 
to 2.9 million at the end of last year. This "real job deficit" 
is 1.7 million higher than the number of unemployed given by the 
official statistics from Nuremberg, which put the number of 
unemployed people in the east at some 1.2 million at the end of 
1993. The real statistics include those citizens who 
participate in job-promotion schemes offered by the labor 
offices or who commute to western Germany, the DGB noted in 
Berlin on Wednesday [2 February]. 
  In Saxony, approximately 790,000 are "underemployed," in 
Saxony Anhalt 540,000, in Thuringia 510,000, in Brandenburg 
455,000, in Mecklenburg Western Pomerania 365,000, and in the 
eastern part of Berlin some 275,000. The situation is most 
favorable in Dresden, where the job deficit was 23.6 percent at 
the end of 1993. Second came Leipzig (28.4 percent deficit), 
while, with an unemployment deficit of 41.3 percent, the Suhl 
region in Thuringia came at the bottom of the list. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

