<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Car Bomb Injures Spanish Embassy Driver </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0302120594 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1134 GMT 3 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0302120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Paper Bomb at Spanish Embassy"] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 3 Feb (ANSA) -- A paper bomb exploded under a 
diplomatic car outside the Spanish embassy in Rome at around 10 
o'clock [0900 GMT] this morning, injuring the driver in the 
buttocks. The driver was taken to hospital as police and 
firemen rushed to the scene. 
  The driver was later identified as an Italian employee of 
the 
embassy, Marco Formichella, 34, suffering from cuts and bruises 
after a blast that made a small hole in the road surface and 
split open the side of the car. 
  The bomb is believed to have been a rudimentary device, 
little more than a cardboard box packed with nitrate-based 
explosive, with an electrical detonator (proved by the discovery 
of six small batteries under the car). 
  Investigators are trying to establish whether it was set off 
by a timer, or was attached to the car ignition -- a thesis 
indicated by the fact that it went off as the driver turned the 
key. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

