<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO-Financed Mine Warfare Simulator in Service </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0402120494 Brussels BELGA in French 1801 GMT 3 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0402120494 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed GGD (ADB): "World's First Mine Warfare </F>
Simulator"; as released by Brussels BELGA Database] 
  [Excerpts] Ostend, 3 Feb (BELGA) -- On Thursday [3 
February], the Belgian-Dutch school of mine warfare based in 
Ostend put into commission a powerful simulator that naval 
officials say is the only one of its kind in the world. 
  This military school, which is renowned throughout the world 
for its marine mine warfare training, can now use a computer to 
simulate the maneuvers of a whole fleet. [passage omitted] 
  Belgian and Dutch naval officials proudly explained on 
Thursday: "With all its possibilities and its exceptional 
performance, this simulator is the only one of its kind in NATO, 
and indeed in the world. The ships and different types of 
sensors and weapons systems can all be simulated by the computer 
database, and the consoles are of a universal type. It will 
even be able to accurately simulate future NATO systems in a 
very realistic environment." 
  Officers from both countries participated in the design of 
this new tool, developed by the American company CAE Link which 
specializes in simulation. 
  The construction of the simulator launched on Thursday was 
financed by NATO, in return for which the allied navies can hire 
the system to train their own crews. [passage omitted] 
  The simulator can also display on screen the image, in fact 
the "virtual reality," sent back by the camera on a 
minisubmarine sent out to hunt for mines on the sea bed. 
[passage omitted] 
  This system also makes it possible for crews to discover 
potential new operations areas. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

