<H3> <TI>   Six Bundeswehr Soldiers To Go to Georgia as Observers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202185494 Hamburg DPA in German 1421 GMT 2 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0202185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- Bundeswehr soldiers will for the first time 
be sent to the territory of the former USSR on behalf of the 
United Nations. The cabinet decided today to dispatch six 
soldiers as unarmed military observers to the war zone in 
Georgia. According to government spokesman Dieter Vogel, the 
German contingent will include four military observers and one 
medical officer. They will form part of a UN contingent of 
about 60 soldiers from 10 nations. 
  There will be no constitutional problems over the observer 
status of the mission: This is only a "diplomatic mission" and 
no blue helmet operation is involved, the dispatch does not 
conflict with the government's position not to send soldiers to 
states on whose territory German troops fought in the past, 
Vogel pointed out. Incidentally, the Germans did not invade 
Georgia during World War II, he stressed. 
  Georgia's existence as a state is threatened by the 
separatist republics of Abkhazia and South Ossetia, which want 
to merge with Russia. 

</TEXT>

