<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Disagrees With Ruehe Over Bundeswehr Strength </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302211794 Hamburg DPA in German 2033 GMT 3 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0302211794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cologne -- Unlike Defense Minister Volker Ruehe 
(Christian Democratic Union), Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel 
(Free Democratic Party of Germany) believes that a Bundeswehr 
strength of 370,000 men should be "preserved by all means." In 
an interview with the Cologne EXPRESS (Friday edition), the 
minister stated that he is aware of the defense minister's 
financial worries and concerns. Yet he added that, in the event 
of a further reduction of the Bundeswehr, the constitutional 
stipulation of equality in conscription would sooner or later 
become a problem. 
  It must be determined what troop strength is needed for what 
purpose, and then the financial aspect must be discussed, and 
not the other way round, under the motto: "How much money do we 
have, and how many soldiers can we afford for that?" 
  Ruehe stated in Bonn on Wednesday [2 February], that, in 
order to cut defense expenditure, the strength of the Bundeswehr 
should be reduced to 345,000 soldiers by the end of 1994 and not 
to 370,000, as originally planned. 

</TEXT>

