<H3> <TI>   Education Minister Resigns for Health Reasons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302163894 Hamburg DPA in German 1532 GMT 3 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0302163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- Education Minister Rainer Ortleb (Free 
Democratic Party of Germany) resigned today. In a short 
statement by the Free Democratic Party of Germany [FDP] to 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, the 49-year-old minister declared that 
he decided to take this step upon the advice of his doctor. 
Thus, he submitted a request to the chancellor requesting his 
discharge from the minister's office to the federal president. 
  Ortleb informed FDP Chairman Klaus Kinkel that he has also 
resigned from his position as FDP chairman in 
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania. According to FDP spokesman 
Hans-Rolf Goebel, Kinkel took note of the two decisions with 
regret and respect and thanked Ortleb for the work he has 
performed. Kinkel expressed the hope that Ortleb will continue 
to make his "indispensable contribution" to completing German 
unity in the party's Executive Committee and the Bundestag group. 
  In November, Ortleb was hospitalized because of a 
circulatory 
collapse and later because of pneumonia. At the beginning of 
January, however, he resumed his official duties. According to 
information received by DPA, State Secretary Fritz Schaumann of 
the Education Ministry (FDP/47) and FDP Deputy Chairman Wolfgang 
Gerhardt are considered possible successors. 

</TEXT>

