<H3> <TI>   Most Italians Favor UN Military Intervention in FRY </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0302131694 Milan CORRIERE DELLA SERA in Italian 2 Feb 94 p 
7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0302131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Milan CORRIERE DELLA SERA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Italians Say Yes To Intervention"] </F>
  [Text] Milan -- More than 50 percent of Italians are in 
favor of an armed UN intervention "aimed at ending war in 
Bosnia." Within this large slice of the population, 
three-fourths are also in favor of the involvement of Italian 
troops in a possible UN intervention, whereas only 17 percent -- 
faced with the possibility of Italian troops being used -- 
change their minds and say no. 
  This is the altogether surprising result of a survey 
conducted by Doxa on behalf of TG3 [TV news], which broadcast 
the results yesterday evening. Fifty-one percent, therefore, 
want air raids and a UN intervention to take place. Among the 
male population, this percentage rises to 58. The more educated 
the interviewees are, the more they like the idea of 
intervention. Only 32 percent of Italians are against 
intervention, while 17 percent did not express any preferences. 

</TEXT>

