<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Group of Professionals Form National Unity Party </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0302153194 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1455 GMT 3 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0302153194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "National Unity Party Formed"] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 3 Feb (ANSA) -- As of today, yet another new 
political movement has been formed as Italy prepares for early 
general elections March 27-28. A group of professional people 
have banded together in what they are calling the National Unity 
Party. 
  The announcement was made at a press conference called here 
Thursday [3 February] by Raffaele D'Ambrosio, a doctor and 
secretary of the new movement; Franz Ciminieri, a literature 
professor and president of the movement; and Pasquale Ciampa, a 
criminal lawyer and a member of the group's political office. 
There are a lot of people in the country who are fed up with 
the old way of doing politics, the sectarianism and politics 
treated as entertainment, and who instead believe that politics 
is meant to be the maximum expression of social and economic 
requirements, D'Ambrosio said. 
  National Unity has been created as an alternative to those 
that call themselves "progressive" and as a counter to any kind 
of separatism, as the real political problem in Italy is the 
threat of national disunity, he continued. 
  The group's platform will rest upon the defense of the 
nation 
against international specualtion, and the refusal of state 
interference within a framework of social justice, D'Ambrosio 
went on. On the economic front, National Unity is for the 
defense of small- and medium-sized private companies and the 
defense of agriculture as an essential element of the economy. 
  The new party is not nationalistic in a cultural sense, but 
only insofar as economic needs must be met, D'Ambrosio explained. 
  National Unity intends to appeal to all the forces of the 
liberal-democratic pole to rediscover politics in terms of 
national unity and above all, economic unity, he concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

