<F P=101> Switzerland </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Wants Palestinian Bank in Switzerland </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0202142394 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1727 GMT 1 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0202142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed rp: "Palestinian Bank: Yasir 'Arafat </F>
Requests Swiss Support"; as released by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Geneva, 1 Feb (ATS) -- PLO Chairman Yasir 'Arafat 
wants the Swiss authorities to support reconstruction in 
Palestine and to allow the Palestinian Bank to be established in 
Switzerland. On Tuesday [1 February], during his visit to the 
Arab-Swiss Chamber of Commerce and Industry in Geneva, the 
Palestinian leader reiterated that 12 billion dollars will be 
needed for rebuilding Palestine. The issue had already been 
broached during the meeting between Mr. 'Arafat and Mr. Stich on 
Monday. 
  Mr. 'Arafat spoke Tuesday in Geneva to more than 600 
representatives of Swiss and foreign industry established in 
Switzerland. According to Elias Attia, secretary general of the 
chamber, all of the country's largest companies were 
represented, from construction to chemicals and banking. 
  The Palestinian leader reiterated that his country would 
have 
a market economy, that it would be democratic, and that it would 
respect the equality of men and women. According to him, the 12 
billion dollars needed for reconstruction will primarily be used 
to reestablish basic infrastructure. Forty percent will come 
from the public sector, while 60 percent will come from private 
investors. 
  On Monday, during his meeting with the president of the 
Confederation in Bern, Yasir 'Arafat had asked Switzerland to 
participate actively in rebuilding the infrastructure "destroyed 
by the occupation" in the territories. "We need your support 
and your experts," he said. According to Mr. Stich, apart from 
the financial aid (60 million Swiss francs) planned by 
Switzerland, the talks also centered on technological 
cooperation and tourism. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

