<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Owen, Stoltenberg: `Full Support' for Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302135294 Paris AFP in English 1345 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302135294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, Feb 3 (AFP) -- International peace 
negotiators David Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg expressed "full 
support" here Thursday [3 February] for the idea of carrying out 
air strikes to protect UN peacekeepers in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  "Close air support has the full support of Mr. Stoltenberg 
and myself," Lord Owen told reporters after he and Stoltenberg, 
who have tried unsuccessfully to broker a peace agreement 
between Bosnia's warring factions, met here with Romanian 
Foreign Minister Teodor Melescanu. 
  He added however, "We would be much happier if we can 
achieve 
the UN mandate without that." 
  Lord Owen, who represents the European Community, said: 
"What has been agreed by the UN Security Council is that there 
should be a close air support" and "that UN forces, when charged 
with a UN mandate, have the right to protection for themselves 
and for carrying out the mandate of the Security Council." 
  He said: "These are air strikes that we'll take primarily in 
a defensive position." 
  Stoltenberg, who represents the United Nations, arrived here 
with Lord Owen late Wednesday as part of a tour of several 
countries neighbouring ex-Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

