<H3> <TI>   Secretary Faults U.S. Delay on Open Sky Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM0302145894 London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH in English 3 Feb 94 
p 21 </F>

<F P=103> PM0302145894 </F>
<F P=104>  London THE DAILY TELEGRAPH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "`U.S. Stalling on Open Sky Policy'"] </F>
  [Text] The United States government is holding up efforts 
to open up the skies and bring lower air fares for travellers, 
John MacGregor, the Transport Secretary, said yesterday. 
  He told the Commons Transport Select Committee that Britain 
is keen to give U.S. airlines freedom to fly into regional 
airports. In return, Britain wants greater access to U.S. 
destinations. "We have offered an immediate lifting of all 
restrictions on services to all airports in the UK except 
Heathrow and Gatwick," Mr MacGregor said. 
  "I very much regret that we have not had a positive response 
from the United States to these proposals. Nor, indeed, have 
they been able to agree a date for talks to resume," he added. 
  American airlines argue that Heathrow and Gatwick are what 
they want because of their strategic value as a hub to the rest 
of Europe. 

</TEXT>

