<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Calls For Troop Strength of 370,000 Men </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402092894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0054 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cologne (DDP/ADN)--Federal Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel has called for the maintenance of Bundeswehr troop 
strength at 370,000 men. Kinkel told the Cologne newspaper 
EXPRESS (Friday [4 February] edition) that he recognized the 
financial difficulties and the concerns of Defense Minister 
Volker Ruehe. However, in his view it is "imperative to 
maintain" a troop strength of 370,000 men. If the Bundeswehr is 
reduced any further, it would be difficult, sooner or later, to 
meet the constitutional obligation to meet defense requirements, 
he explained. "We must establish what sort of troop strength we 
need for which tasks, and then money can be discussed. It should 
not be the other way round, under the motto `How much money do 
we have, and how many soldiers can we afford on that.'" 
  Regarding plans by the defense minister not to take part in 
any more international UN missions on cost grounds, Kinkel said 
that if the United Nations should ask the German Government to 
participate in another mission such as Somalia this year, "we 
cannot say no from the start on cost grounds." Such a request 
must be thoroughly considered on an individual basis and in the 
light of the constitutional situation and all the circumstances 
involved. 

</TEXT>

